.TH "BEEP" "1" "April 2026" "beep 0.1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
beep \- play tones through the default audio device
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]beep\f[R] [\f[I]OPTIONS\f[R]]\&...
.PP
\f[B]beep\f[R] [\f[I]OPTIONS\f[R]] [\f[B]\-n\f[R]] [\f[I]OPTIONS\f[R]]
\&...
.PP
\f[B]beep\f[R] [\f[B]\-h\f[R]|\f[B]\-\-help\f[R]]
.PP
\f[B]beep\f[R] [\f[B]\-v\f[R]|\f[B]\-\-version\f[R]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]beep\f[R] plays one or more tones through the system\(cqs default
audio output device.
It is a cross\-platform reimplementation of the classic Unix
\f[I]beep\f[R](1) utility by Johnathan Nightingale, which drove the PC
speaker directly.
Because modern systems rarely have PC speakers, this version uses the
standard audio subsystem via the \f[I]rodio\f[R] library, working on
Linux, macOS, and Windows.
.PP
The generated tone is a square wave passed through a high\-pass and
low\-pass filter, approximating the frequency response of a small
magnetic speaker or piezoelectric buzzer typical of PC\-era beepers.
.PP
All durations are in milliseconds, frequencies in hertz, and repetition
counts are dimensionless.
.PP
If an option is specified more than once, the last occurrence wins.
So \f[B]beep \-f 200 \-f 300\f[R] beeps at 300 Hz.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\-f\f[R] \f[I]FREQ\f[R]
Frequency in hertz.
Default: 440.
.TP
\f[B]\-l\f[R] \f[I]LEN\f[R]
Tone length in milliseconds.
Default: 200.
.TP
\f[B]\-r\f[R] \f[I]REPS\f[R]
Number of repetitions.
Default: 1.
.TP
\f[B]\-d\f[R] \f[I]DELAY\f[R]
Delay in milliseconds between beeps.
No delay occurs after the final beep.
Default: 100.
.TP
\f[B]\-D\f[R] \f[I]DELAY\f[R]
Same as \f[B]\-d\f[R], but also applies the delay after the final beep.
Useful when chaining \f[I]beep\f[R] commands together, where consistent
timing between invocations matters.
.TP
\f[B]\-s\f[R]
Read stdin line by line, echoing each line to stdout and beeping once
per line.
Useful in pipelines.
.TP
\f[B]\-c\f[R]
Read stdin byte by byte, echoing each byte to stdout and beeping once
per byte.
.TP
\f[B]\-n\f[R], \f[B]\-\-new\f[R]
Start a new beep with default values.
All following options apply to the new beep.
This allows chaining multiple different beeps in a single invocation.
See EXAMPLES.
.TP
\f[B]\-e\f[R] \f[I]DEVICE\f[R], \f[B]\-\-device\f[R]=\f[I]DEVICE\f[R]
Accepted for compatibility with the original \f[I]beep\f[R]; ignored.
There is no underlying PC speaker device to select.
.TP
\f[B]\-\-verbose\f[R], \f[B]\-\-debug\f[R]
Print a diagnostic line to stderr before each beep, showing the
frequency, length, repetitions, and delay.
Useful when debugging scripts or chained beep invocations.
The output is compatible with the original \f[I]beep\f[R] program.
.TP
\f[B]\-v\f[R], \f[B]\-V\f[R], \f[B]\-\-version\f[R]
Print version and exit.
.TP
\f[B]\-h\f[R], \f[B]\-\-help\f[R]
Print usage information and exit.
.SH EXAMPLES
Play the default beep (440 Hz for 200 ms):
.IP
.EX
beep
.EE
.PP
Play a higher\-pitched beep like the traditional terminal bell:
.IP
.EX
beep \-f 750
.EE
.PP
Play three half\-second beeps at 1 kHz with 200 ms between them:
.IP
.EX
beep \-f 1000 \-l 500 \-r 3 \-d 200
.EE
.PP
Chain three different notes to play a short melody:
.IP
.EX
beep \-f 523 \-l 200 \-n \-f 659 \-l 200 \-n \-f 784 \-l 400
.EE
.PP
Beep whenever a line of build output is produced, preserving the output
for logging:
.IP
.EX
make 2>&1 | beep \-s | tee build.log
.EE
.PP
Beep on completion of a long\-running command:
.IP
.EX
long\-running\-command; beep \-r 3
.EE
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
\f[B]0\f[R]
Success.
.TP
\f[B]non\-zero\f[R]
Argument parsing failed, audio device could not be opened, or an I/O
error occurred.
.PP
On Unix, \f[I]beep\f[R] resets SIGPIPE to its default disposition, so it
terminates silently when a downstream process in a pipeline closes
stdin.
.SH LIMITATIONS
For compatibility with the original \f[I]beep\f[R], the
\f[B]\-e\f[R]/\f[B]\-\-device\f[R] flag is accepted but does nothing, as
there is no underlying PC speaker to select.
